                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/2639: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The President of the Technical Board</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stevens</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-08-15T14:00:00+08:26">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 15, 1922—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 16—2:24 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Fifteen thousand Chinese forces supposed to guard railway mutinied at one of the
                    railway stations, killed commanders, looted station <pb facs="1031" n="911"
                        xml:id="pg_911"/> and town, moved to another station, destroyed telegraph,
                    stopping traffic. On request Chinese military commander does nothing. Mutineers
                    are now loose in the hills without money or food but with arms and ammunition
                    and further serious trouble will take place. Chinese forces continually beat up
                    and rob railway employees and nothing can be done to prevent. Apparently no
                    consideration is given by the Department to my telegram of June 30, 2 p.m. Copy
                    furnished Peking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stevens</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
